<exercise checkit-seed="0027" checkit-slug="M1" checkit-title="Multiplying matrices">
  <statement>
    <p>Of the following three matrices, only two may be multiplied.
      <md><mrow>A= \left[\begin{array}{cc}
3 &amp; 5 \\
1 &amp; 4 \\
1 &amp; 1 \\
-3 &amp; -4
\end{array}\right]  &amp; &amp; B= \left[\begin{array}{cc}
4 &amp; 1 \\
0 &amp; 1 \\
1 &amp; -1
\end{array}\right]  &amp; &amp; C= \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
3 &amp; -4 &amp; 5 \\
1 &amp; -1 &amp; 1 \\
-2 &amp; 3 &amp; -3 \\
2 &amp; -6 &amp; 6
\end{array}\right] </mrow></md>
      Explain which two can be multiplied and why. Then show how to find their product.</p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <me>CB= \left[\begin{array}{cc}
17 &amp; -6 \\
5 &amp; -1 \\
-11 &amp; 4 \\
14 &amp; -10
\end{array}\right] </me>
  </answer>
</exercise>

